<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="practical-determining-distribution-abundance">Practical: Determining Distribution &amp; Abundance</h2><ul><li><p>Finding out about the <span class="popovers" data-content="This is the number of different species, or the number of individuals of a particular species, found within a given area." data-title="Abundance" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">abundance</span> and <span class="popovers" data-content="The distribution of a species is where it is found within an ecosystem. This will most likely be wherever the suitable habitat of that species is found." data-title="Distribution" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">distribution</span> of species can be achieved by counting all of the organisms present in a habitat</p></li><li><p>This is possible for areas that are very small or where the species are very large</p></li><li><p>For larger and more complex habitats it is not possible<b> </b>to find, identify, and count every organism that is present</p></li><li><p>When this is the case <b>sampling</b> can be used to make an <b>estimate </b>for the total species numbers</p></li></ul><h4 id="sampling">Sampling</h4><ul><li><p>Sampling is a method of investigating the <b>abundance and distribution of species and populations</b></p></li><li><p>There are two different types of sampling</p><ul><li><p><b>Random</b></p></li><li><p><b>Systematic</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>In <b>random sampling</b> the positions of the sampling points are selected <b>at random</b></p><ul><li><p>This method avoids<b> bias</b> by the person that is carrying out the sampling</p></li><li><p>Bias <b>can affect the results</b> e.g.</p><ul><li><p>A student might choose to carry out samples in a particular location because it looks interesting, and this might give the impression that the habitat contains more species than it really does</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>In <b>systematic sampling </b>the positions of the sampling points are located at <b>fixed intervals</b> throughout the sampling site</p><ul><li><p>This avoids accidentally missing out sections of habitat due to chance</p></li><li><p>Systematic sampling allows researchers to investigate the<b> effect of the presence of certain environmental features</b> on species distribution e.g. by taking samples <b>along a line</b> that extends away from an environmental feature such as a river</p><ul><li><p>A line of this type is known as a <b>transect</b></p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>When a sampling area is <b>reasonably uniform</b> then<b> random sampling </b>is the best choice</p></li><li><p>Random sample sites can be selected by</p><ul><li><p>Laying out a <b>grid</b> over the area to be studied</p></li><li><p>Generating <b>random number co-ordinates</b> </p></li><li><p>Placing sample sites in the grid squares that match the random number co-ordinates</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Random and Systematic Sampling" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="409" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Random-and-Systematic-Sampling.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Random sampling involves selecting sample sites at random while systematic sampling involves placing sample sites at regular intervals.</b></i></p><h4 id="determining-distribution-and-abundance">Determining distribution and abundance</h4><ul><li><p>The distribution and abundance of a species in an area can be assessed using different practical methods:</p><ul><li><p>Frame and point <b>quadrats</b></p></li><li><p>Line and belt <b>transects</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="frame-quadrats">Frame quadrats</h4><ul><li><p>A<b> frame quadrat</b> is a <b>square frame</b> that is placed within the area to be studied to provide a <b>sample</b></p><ul><li><p>Quadrats are used to study the <b>distribution</b> of <span class="popovers" data-content="A sessile organism is fixed in place, or immobile" data-title="Sessile" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">sessile</span><span class="popovers" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition"> </span>organisms</p></li><li><p>Quadrats can be <b>different sizes</b> depending on the species being studied</p><ul><li><p>A 1 m² quadrat can be used to study small organisms such as herbaceous plants in a grassland or limpets on a rocky shore</p></li><li><p>A 400 m² quadrat can be used to study large organisms such as trees</p><ul><li><p>Quadrats like this will usually be marked out with string rather than a frame!</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>Frame quadrats can be placed in a habitat <b>randomly, </b>e.g. using random co-ordinates, or <b>systematically,</b> e.g. along a transect</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Quadrat in use" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="683" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Quadrat-in-use_1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>A frame quadrat can be used to measure abundance and distribution</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Scientists can record <b>different types of data</b> from a frame quadrat depending on the aim of a study and the species involved</p><ul><li><p><b>Presence or absence</b> of a species</p></li><li><p><b>Species frequency</b>; how many individuals are in the quadrat</p></li><li><p><b>Species abundance</b>; measured on a scale called the <b>ACFOR</b> scale on which species are recorded as being abundant, common, frequent, occasional, rare, or none</p></li><li><p><b>Percentage cover</b>; the percentage of the quadrat covered by a species</p><ul><li><p>Quadrats can be divided up into smaller squares to allow percentage cover to be assessed more easily</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Percentage Cover in Quadrat" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="733" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat_1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Abundance in a frame quadrat can be assessed by measuring percentage cover</b></i></p><h4 id="point-quadrats">Point quadrats</h4><ul><li><p>A<b> point quadrat</b> is a vertical frame with holes across the top through which <b>pins</b> are lowered</p><ul><li><p>This is useful in areas with <b>dense plant cover</b> as the ground may be difficult to study using a frame quadrat </p></li><li><p>Point quadrats can be placed in a habitat <b>randomly, </b>e.g. using random co-ordinates, or <b>systematically,</b> e.g. along a transect</p></li></ul></li><li><p>When a lowered pin touches a species, that species is recorded as being present</p><ul><li><p>If several species are touching the pin then all of those species are recorded</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Point quadrats can be used to measure abundance in the following ways</p><ul><li><p>The <b>number of individuals</b> of a species present</p><ul><li><p>Each individual that touches a pin is recorded </p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Percentage cover</b> of a species</p><ul><li><p>The number of pins touched by a species is divided by the total number of pins used</p></li><li><p>Most point quadrats have ten pins, so if all the pins are used then a species touching one pin counts as 10 percent cover</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="point-quadrat" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="724" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="point-quadrat.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/point-quadrat.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Point quadrats can be used to measure the number of individuals of a species or percentage cover.</b></i></p><h4 id="transects">Transects</h4><ul><li><p><b>Transects</b> are lines laid out across a site that can be used to measure abundance and distribution<b> across a habitat</b></p><ul><li><p>Transects are useful for determining <b>how species abundance and distribution might change along a gradient</b> e.g. at increasing distances from a field margin or perpendicular to the water's edge on a rocky shore</p></li></ul></li><li><p>To carry out a<b> transect</b>, a tape measure is laid out along the gradient of interest, and samples are taken along the line</p></li><li><p>There are different ways of carrying out transect studies</p><ul><li><p><b>Continuous line transect</b></p><ul><li><p><b>Every species </b>touching the tape measure is recorded</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Interrupted line transect</b></p><ul><li><p>Species touching the line <b>at regular intervals</b>, e.g. every metre, are recorded</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Continuous belt transect</b></p><ul><li><p>Frame quadrats are placed <b>end-to-end</b> along the line </p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Interrupted belt transect</b></p><ul><li><p>Frame or point quadrats are placed <b>at regular intervals</b>, e.g. every metre, along the line</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Line and Belt Transects" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="575" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Line-and-Belt-Transects.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Line-and-Belt-Transects.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Interrupted line and belt transects can be used to measure abundance and distribution of species along a line across a habitat</b></i></p><h4 id="measuring-abiotic-factors">Measuring abiotic factors</h4><ul><li><p>The distribution and abundance of species in a habitat are affected by <span class="popovers" data-content="Concerned with the non-living part of the environment." data-title="Abiotic Factors" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">abiotic</span> factors</p></li><li><p>When investigating the impact of an abiotic factors on species abundance and distribution it is important to <b>measure the relevant abiotic factors</b> at the sample sites</p><ul><li><p>It is only necessary to record relevant abiotic factors</p><ul><li><p>A study may only be interested in one particular abiotic factor</p></li><li><p>Some abiotic factors may not be relevant in certain habitats e.g. water turbidity (cloudiness) will not be relevant in a woodland habitat</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>Abiotic factors can be measured using <b>specialised equipment</b> and <b>techniques</b></p></li></ul><p><b>Measuring Abiotic Factors Table</b></p><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="measuring-abiotic-factors-table" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1194" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/05/measuring-abiotic-factors-table.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><h4 id="representing-results">Representing results</h4><ul><li><p>The results of an investigation into the distribution and abundance of organisms can be represented visually using a type of graph known as a <b>kite diagram</b></p></li><li><p>Kite diagrams can show both <b>distribution </b>and <b>abundance</b></p><ul><li><p>The distribution of a species along a transect can be shown by its <b>position along a central horizontal line</b> in each section of a kite diagram</p><ul><li><p>Each section represents a different species </p></li><li><p>The <b>distance along the transect is given on the x-axis</b>, to which the horizontal line is parallel</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The abundance of a species can be shown by the <b>width of the 'kite'</b> around the central horizontal line</p><ul><li><p>The shape is referred to as a kite because it extends an <b>equal distance</b> on each side of the central horizontal line</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>Additional sections can be added to a kite diagram to show the <b>changes in abiotic factors </b>at different points along a transect e.g. the height above sea level or the pH of soil</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="kite-diagram-transect-data" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1014" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="kite-diagram-transect-data.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2023/08/kite-diagram-transect-data.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Kite diagrams can be used to provide a visual representation of both abundance and distribution of species, as well as changes to abiotic factors such as elevation</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>You could be asked to describe or design an investigation that could be used to measure the effect of a specific abiotic factor on species abundance or distribution, so make sure that you know the circumstances in which each sampling technique would be used, and how to use it.</p><p>Remember that when describing a practical you should always consider:</p><ul><li><p>How you will change the <b>independent variable</b></p><ul><li><p>In this context you might be measuring a change in the independent variable, or abiotic factor, rather than causing the change yourself</p></li><li><p>Note that this might not be relevant if you have just been asked to measure the abundance of a species in one habitat</p></li></ul></li><li><p>How you will measure the <b>dependent variable</b> </p></li><li><p>How you will ensure that your <b>results are valid</b></p></li></ul></div></div></div></div>